
# Push a Local Folder to GitHub (Mac)

## 1. Open Terminal and go to the project folder

```bash
cd ~/robotarm
```

Verify you're in the correct folder:

```bash
pwd
ls
```

---

## 2. Initialize Git

Create a Git repository in the folder:

```bash
git init
```

This creates the hidden `.git` directory.

---

## 3. Add files to Git

Stage all files:

```bash
git add .
```

Check what will be committed:

```bash
git status
```

---

## 4. Create the first commit

```bash
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

---

## 5. Configure Git identity (recommended)

Set your GitHub identity:

```bash
git config --global user.name "Chenhao Tang"
git config --global user.email "chenhaotang1@gmail.com"
```

Verify:

```bash
git config --global --list
```

---

## 6. Create an SSH key (one-time setup)

Generate a key:

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "chenhaotang1@gmail.com"
```

Press Enter to accept the default location:

```text
~/.ssh/id_ed25519
```

---

## 7. Copy the public key

Display the public key:

```bash
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```

Copy the entire line.

---

## 8. Add the SSH key to GitHub

Go to:

[GitHub SSH Keys Settings](https://github.com/settings/keys?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

1. Click **New SSH key**
2. Give it a name (e.g., "MacBook")
3. Paste the public key
4. Save

---

## 9. Test SSH authentication

```bash
ssh -T git@github.com
```

Successful output:

```text
Hi henry2772! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.
```

---

## 10. Connect the local repo to GitHub

Add the remote repository:

```bash
git remote add origin git@github.com:hku-engg2202/RobotArm.git
```

Or if a remote already exists:

```bash
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:hku-engg2202/RobotArm.git
```

Verify:

```bash
git remote -v
```

---

## 11. Push to GitHub

Push the current branch:

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

The `-u` sets the upstream branch so future pushes are simpler.

---

# Future Workflow

After making changes:

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Describe the change"
git push
```

That's it.

---

# Useful Commands

Check status:

```bash
git status
```

See commit history:

```bash
git log --oneline
```

See remote repository:

```bash
git remote -v
```

Pull latest changes from GitHub:

```bash
git pull
```

Ignore macOS `.DS_Store` files:

```bash
echo ".DS_Store" >> .gitignore
git rm --cached .DS_Store
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Ignore .DS_Store"
git push
```

Now your Mac is properly configured for GitHub SSH, so future repositories only need steps **1–4, 10, and 11**. The SSH key setup (steps 6–9) is usually a one-time setup per machine.
